crypt-mt - minimal stream cipher based on a (thought to be) cryptographically-
secure transformation of the Mersenne Twister PRNG

This package assumes one has already placed a version of Geoff Kuenning's
'mtwist' MT implementation in a directory parallel to this code, eg:

+
|
+-mtwist-1.4/
|
+-mt-crypt/

An archive of Mr. Kuenning's mtwist version 1.4 is included along with this
distribution for completeness' sake. It is licensed under the LGPL.

To build, from mt-crypt/ just run 'make'. The makefile will attempt to build
'mtc.c' and '../mtwist-1.4/mtwist.c', placing the executable in the same
directory as 'Makefile'.

Build tested on cygwin under Windows 7 32-bit only at time of writing.

Security
--------
The randomness of the resulting encrypted stream passes the 'randstdev'
randomness test tool

[http://sourceforge.net/projects/randstdev]

... when encrypting a test text file of 'War and Peace' as supplied
from archive.org and included in this distribution:

$ ../randstdev/programs/randstdev.exe <wrnpc11.txt
FAIL Average = 0.000000 +- 0.000000

$ ./mtc <wrnpc11.txt >wrnpc11.txt.mtc

$ ../randstdev/programs/randstdev.exe <wrnpc11.txt.mtc
PASS Average = 256.020320 +- 2.281723


Usage
-----
$ mtc {key} <plaintext >ciphertext

** NOTE this program will use a DEFAULT KEY (see mtc.c) if none is supplied.

** ALSO NOTE the key, if shorter than that required to fully initialize the MT
PRNG state (624 32-bit words, will be expanded via simple repetition to fill
said state. A more secure method generating more 'random' initial state, such
as iteratively generating SHA1 hashes on the supplied key, then on each
preceding SHA1 and concatenating those hashes to fill the entire state
would likely be a better way to initialize the PRNG.

-Russ Magee (rmagee@gmail.com)

